				<textarea class="markdown">
						Esports, competitive video gaming, has become incredibly popular.  Newzoo estimates that the global audience for esports will reach 1.1 billion by 2021<sup>1,2</sup>.  Estimates suggest that 90% of children in the U.S. play video games regularly<sup>1,3</sup>.
						A study done by BMJ Open Sport & Exercise Medicine reports that esports athletes are at risk of developing overuse injuries. The study suggests that the most common health issue was eye fatigue, then neck and back pain, and wrist and hand pain<sup>3</sup>.

						Arm, hand and wrist injuries affecting gamers include:

						- gamer's thumb
						- carpal tunnel syndrome
						- trigger finger
						- tennis elbow
						- de Quervain's tenosynovitis
						- cubital tunnel syndrome (ulnar neuritis)



						###Gamer's Thumb

						Also known as DeQuervain's tenosynovitis,

						###Carpal Tunnel Syndrome


						This develops as the median nerve becomes compressed from progressively worsening inflammation of the wrist flexor tendons

						###Trigger Finger

						A callus forms on the flexor tendon which can cause catching

						###Tennis Elbow

						Also known as lateral epicondylitis

						###Cubital Tunnel Syndrome

						Also known as ulnar neuritis.  This is often a result of gamers resting their elbow(s) on a surface while holding a controller or using a keyboard







